Las Vegas is a gambling and tourist destination for the Greater Los Angeles area.<ref name="LAT 2023-12-05">{{Cite news |last=Uranga |first=Rachel |date=2023-12-05 |title=SoCal to Vegas in two hours? High-speed rail comes closer to reality with $3-billion award |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-12-05/socal-to-vegas-in-two-hours-high-speed-rail-comes-closer-to-reality-with-3-billion-award |access-date=2023-12-26 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US}}</ref> Interstate 15 is a direct route between the two regions.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gillan |first=Jeff |date=2021-10-22 |title=High-speed rail takes step to link Las Vegas with Los Angeles |work=KSNV |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/high-speed-rail-takes-step-to-link-vegas-with-la-10-22-2021 |access-date=2021-10-24}}</ref>{{r|Travel Tips}}{{r|Forb 2020/08/22}} An estimated 50 million people travel between Los Angeles and Las Vegas annually, with 85% using a car.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Ohnsman |first=Alan |date=April 25, 2023 |title='The Greenest Bullet Train In The World': Wes Edens Wants To Kickstart U.S. High-Speed Rail With A Vegas-L.A. Line |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2023/04/25/the-greenest-bullet-train-in-the-world-wes-edens-wants-to-kickstart-us-high-speed-rail-with-a-vegas-la-line/ |access-date=2023-04-26 |magazine=Forbes |language=en}}</ref> Travel by automobile takes over four hours<ref name="SB 2022-11-02">{{Cite news |last=Newton |first=Damien |date=2022-11-02 |title=Brightline Releases Environmental Documents for High-Speed Rail from Victorville to Las Vegas |language=en-US |work=Streetsblog California |url=https://cal.streetsblog.org/2022/11/02/brightline-releases-environmental-documents-for-high-speed-rail-from-victorville-to-las-vegas/ |access-date=2022-11-03}}</ref> while scheduled buses cover the route in five to seven hours.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Los Angeles to Las Vegas Travel Options |url=http://gocalifornia.about.com/od/topcalifornia/qt/la_to_lv.htm |access-date=October 24, 2010 |publisher=About.com |archive-date=January 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112052044/http://gocalifornia.about.com/od/topcalifornia/qt/la_to_lv.htm |url-status=dead }}</ref> Interstate 15 is an important [[Road transport|freight route]], so reduced congestion on the route would benefit the [[supply chain]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Lassen |first=David |date=2024-04-24 |title=Governments in alignment as Brightline West work begins |url=https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/governments-in-alignment-as-brightline-west-work-begins/ |access-date=2024-04-25 |magazine=Trains |language=en-US}}</ref>

The highway carries heavy traffic on Thursday, Friday, and Sunday, which causes significant delays.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Interstate 15 Northbound&nbsp;– Barstow to Nevada |url=http://www.aaroads.com/california/i-015ng_ca.html |access-date=October 24, 2010 |publisher=AARoads}}</ref> Motorists returning to Los Angeles on Sunday can create an {{convert|18|mile|adj=mid}} backup.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dowd |first=Katie |date=2022-11-27 |title=18-mile gridlock on Calif.-Nevada border amid slammed travel day |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/gridlock-traffic-on-calif-nevada-border-17613840.php |access-date=2022-11-27 |work=SFGATE |language=en-US}}</ref> Airlines have direct flights, but traffic and security at the airport add time to the short flight.{{r|Forbes 2022/01/24}}<ref name="Travel Tips">{{Cite news |last=Jernigan |first=Meg |date=December 21, 2017 |title=How to Travel From Las Vegas to Los Angeles |language=en |work=Travel Tips – USA Today |url=https://traveltips.usatoday.com/travel-las-vegas-los-angeles-36739.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905115004/http://traveltips.usatoday.com/travel-las-vegas-los-angeles-36739.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 5, 2017 |access-date=2020-10-05 }}</ref> Las Vegas lost its last passenger train service in 1997 when [[Amtrak]] canceled the ''[[Desert Wind]]''.<ref name="AP 2021-04-18">{{Cite news |date=2021-04-18 |title=US infrastructure plan spurs talk of Vegas-LA rail service |work=AP News |url=https://apnews.com/article/joe-biden-los-angeles-transportation-california-victorville-e32e4b49fca442991650eaac6438bb26 |access-date=2021-04-19}}</ref>

==Brightline project==
In September 2018, [[Fortress Investment Group]], which owns an inter-city rail route in Florida called [[Brightline]], announced that it would acquire the federally approved XpressWest rail corridor project, indicating that it would begin construction of the rail line in the second half of 2020 with expected completion in the second half of 2024. After some delays, groundbreaking began on April 22, 2024 with service expected to start in late 2029.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ritter |first=Ken |date=2024-04-22 |title=Rail spikes hammered, bullet train being built from Sin City to the City of Angels |url=https://apnews.com/article/high-speed-train-vegas-los-angeles-brightline-595913ff2fa3d9001fb89bfab4e6c4d2 |access-date=2024-04-23 |website=AP News |language=en}}</ref> The project is expected to generate around 18,000 jobs at its peak. Los Angeles County finished an environmental assessment for the project in 2016. In October 2019, design plans were almost 30% complete.<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 23, 2019 |title=Virgin Trains USA to Move Ahead on Vegas to Calif. Line |url=https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/virgin-trains-usa-to-move-ahead-on-vegas-to-calif-line/46398 |website=Construction Equipment Guide}}</ref> In September 2020, the line was rebranded to Brightline West, and is being called "a Brightline affiliated company."<ref>{{Cite web |title=West Coast {{!}} Brightline |url=https://www.gobrightline.com/west-coast-expansion |access-date=September 16, 2020 |website=www.gobrightline.com |archive-date=May 6, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210506131526/https://www.gobrightline.com/west-coast-expansion |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="Brightline West Fact Sheet">{{Cite web |title=LA To Vegas Fact Sheet |url=https://www.gobrightline.com/sites/default/files/2020-09/LA_To_Vegas_Fact_Sheet.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210127221735/https://www.gobrightline.com/sites/default/files/2020-09/LA_To_Vegas_Fact_Sheet.pdf |archive-date=January 27, 2021 |access-date=September 16, 2020 |publisher=Brightline}}</ref>

===Funding assistance ===
A high speed line following the Palmdale–Apple Valley–Las Vegas route was included in the 2018 California State Rail Plan as part of the 2040 timeline of projects.<ref>{{Cite web |title=2018 California State Rail Plan (Draft) |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/californiarail/docs/CSRP_PublicReleaseDraft_10112017.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129160329/https://dot.ca.gov/californiarail/docs/CSRP_PublicReleaseDraft_10112017.pdf |archive-date=January 29, 2018 |access-date=September 23, 2019 |publisher=CalTrans}}</ref> Subsequently, the state of California issued tax-exempt, [[private activity bond]]s to XpressWest to partially fund construction.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 21, 2019 |title=State Treasurer Fiona Ma announces CDLAC Board approval of $300M in bonds for Apple Valley-Las Vegas high-speed rail |work=Orange County Breeze |url=http://www.oc-breeze.com/2019/09/21/145082_state-treasurer-fiona-ma-announces-cdlac-board-approval-of-300m-in-bonds-for-victorville-las-vegas-high-speed-rail/ |access-date=September 23, 2019 |archive-date=September 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923183842/http://www.oc-breeze.com/2019/09/21/145082_state-treasurer-fiona-ma-announces-cdlac-board-approval-of-300m-in-bonds-for-victorville-las-vegas-high-speed-rail/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> These bonds are meant to assist private ventures for the public interest.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Varghese |first=Romy |date=December 21, 2021 |title=Fortress-Backed Rail Company Brightline Gets an Ally in California's Treasurer |language=en-US |work=Yahoo News {{!}} Finance |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/fortress-backed-rail-company-brightline-142857504.html |access-date=2021-12-22}}</ref>

In September 2019, it was announced that California would assist the project in funding. In October 2019 California Infrastructure and Economic Development Bank approved $3.25&nbsp;billion in bonds.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 19, 2019 |title=California to assist financing of private California-Vegas train |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/09/19/california-to-assist-financing-of-california-vegas-train/ |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=October 24, 2019 |title=Virgin Trains USA hoping to start construction of train line from Victorville to Las Vegas in 2020 |work=Victor Valley News Group |url=https://www.vvng.com/virgin-trains-usa-hoping-to-start-construction-of-train-line-from-victorville-to-las-vegas-in-2020/}}</ref> In April 2020, California government officials signed off on issuing $600 million in tax-exempt private activity bonds for XpressWest.<ref>{{Cite news |last=O'Connor |first=Devin |date=April 15, 2020 |title=Virgin Hotels Las Vegas Remains Focused on Fall 2020 Opening, Virgin Trains Receives $600M |work=Casino.org |url=https://www.casino.org/news/virgin-hotels-las-vegas-remains-focused-on-fall-2020-opening-virgin-trains-receives-600m/ |access-date=July 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hass |first=Greg |date=July 21, 2020 |title=Financing for DesertXpress line from Las Vegas to Apple Valley takes step forward |url=https://www.8newsnow.com/news/local-news/financing-for-virgin-trains-line-from-las-vegas-to-victorville-takes-step-forward/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200721192525/https://www.8newsnow.com/news/local-news/financing-for-virgin-trains-line-from-las-vegas-to-victorville-takes-step-forward/ |archive-date=July 21, 2020 |access-date=August 9, 2020 |work=KLAS |language=en-US}}</ref> The state of Nevada allocated the company an additional $200&nbsp;million in private activity bonds in July 2020.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Ohnsman |first=Alan |date=July 24, 2020 |title=Los Angeles-To-Las Vegas High-Speed Train Wins $200 Million Nevada Bond Allocation |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2020/07/24/los-angeles-to-las-vegas-high-speed-train-wins-200-million-nevada-bond-allocation/ |magazine=Forbes |access-date=July 29, 2020}}</ref>

Cofounder and co-CEO of Fortress, [[Wes Edens]], estimated the cost of construction at $8&nbsp;billion in 2020.<ref name="Forbes2020" /> In September 2020, up to $3.2&nbsp;billion in the tax-exempt, private activity bonds were offered.<ref name="LVRJ 2020-10-05">{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=2020-10-05 |title=Vegas-to-LA high-speed train could serve as Raiders fan pipeline |language=en-US |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/news-columns/road-warrior/vegas-to-la-high-speed-train-could-serve-as-raiders-fan-pipeline-2138504/ |access-date=2020-10-06}}</ref> In November, it was decided to let the rights for the sale of the bonds lapse.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Horwath |first=Bryan |date=2020-11-02 |title=Las Vegas-California high-speed rail project hits snag |work=Las Vegas Sun |url=https://m.lasvegassun.com/news/2020/nov/02/las-vegas-california-high-speed-rail-project-snag/ |access-date=2020-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mike |date=2020-10-26 |title=Brightline reveals more details about Vegas-to-LA high-speed rail line |language=en-US |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/news-columns/road-warrior/brightline-reveals-more-details-about-vegas-to-la-high-speed-rail-line-2162408/ |access-date=2020-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=2020-12-09 |title=Nevada reallocates $200M in bonds from high-speed rail to affordable housing |language=en-US |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/nevada-reallocates-200m-in-bonds-from-high-speed-rail-to-affordable-housing-2209665/ |access-date=2020-12-10}}</ref> A bond sale was planned for 2021 but was moved to 2022 to allow continued progress on project planning and for the bonds to be more attractive to investors.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=2021-06-22 |title=Las Vegas-LA high-speed rail plan delayed until 2022 |language=en-US |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/las-vegas-la-high-speed-rail-plan-delayed-until-2022-2383729/ |access-date=2021-06-22}}</ref><ref name="VVDP 2021/01/19">{{Cite news |last=De La Cruz |first=Rene Ray |date=January 19, 2021 |title=With revised plan, Brightline eyes 2021 groundbreaking of Apple Valley rail project |language=en-US |work=Victor Valley Daily Press |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/news/2021/01/19/revised-plan-brightline-eyes-2021-groundbreaking-apple-valley-rail-project/4221136001/ |access-date=2021-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Komenda |first=Ed |date=April 9, 2021 |title=Brightline CEO: Vegas-to-LA high-speed rail line still on track to break ground in 2021 |language=en-US |work=Reno Gazette Journal |url=https://www.rgj.com/story/news/2021/04/09/brightline-ceo-vegas-la-high-speed-rail-line-track-2021/7161675002/ |access-date=2021-04-11}}</ref>

[[Los Angeles Metro]] is considering re-programming around $2&nbsp;billion in Measure M funding slated for the High Desert Corridor, a proposed freeway between Victorville and Palmdale, canceled in October 2019, to instead create a development plan for an extension of the XpressWest route between the two cities.<ref>{{Cite news |date=October 6, 2019 |title=Editorial: It was a terrible idea to build a new freeway in Los Angeles County. Now it's on hold for good |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/story/2019-10-06/high-desert-corridor-freeway-stopped |access-date=July 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Linton |first=Joe |date=August 19, 2020 |title=Metro Looks to Shift High Desert Freeway Funds to High-Speed Rail |url=https://la.streetsblog.org/2020/08/19/metro-looks-to-shift-high-desert-freeway-funds-to-high-speed-rail/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200820204137/https://la.streetsblog.org/2020/08/19/metro-looks-to-shift-high-desert-freeway-funds-to-high-speed-rail/ |archive-date=August 20, 2020 |access-date=August 27, 2020 |website=Streetsblog Los Angeles |language=en-US}}</ref>{{r|LVRJ 2021-07-06}}

In February 2023, the company applied for $3.75 billion in funding from [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]].{{r|LVRJ 2023-02-15}} A bipartisan congressional group from Nevada and California wrote a letter in April 2023 in support of the funding.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ritter |first=Ken |date=April 24, 2023 |title=Las Vegas-to-California bullet train gets bipartisan backing |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/vegas-california-high-speed-train-gets-bipartisan-backing-98808373 |access-date=2023-04-25 |work=ABC News |language=en |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In December 2023, the [[United States Department of Transportation]] awarded Brightline West $3 billion of the grant request and in September 2024 signed it.{{r|LAT 2023-12-05}}{{r|LVRJ 2024-09-26}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Luczak |first=Marybeth |date=2024-09-27 |title=FRA Advances Brightline West Project With Signed Agreement |url=https://www.railwayage.com/regulatory/fra-advances-brightline-west-project-with-signed-agreement/ |url-access=subscription |access-date=2024-09-30 |website=[[Railway Age]]}}</ref> In January 2024, Brightline West received $2.5 billion of [[private activity bonds]] from the [[US Department of Transportation]] in addition to $1 billion given in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Seeman |first=Matthew |date=January 23, 2024 |title=$2.5 billion in bonds approved for Brightline West high-speed train to Las Vegas |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/25-billion-in-bonds-approved-for-brightline-west-high-speed-train-to-las-vegas-wes-edens-pete-buttigieg-usdot-transit-southern-california |work=News 3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Luczak |first=Marybeth |date=2024-01-23 |title=Brightline West Lands $2.5B in Private Activity Bonds |url=https://www.railwayage.com/regulatory/brightline-west-lands-2-5b-in-private-activity-bonds/ |url-access=subscription |access-date=2024-09-30 |website=[[Railway Age]]}}</ref> The remainder of the cost (estimated at $12 billion as of April 2024<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/article/high-speed-train-vegas-los-angeles-brightline-595913ff2fa3d9001fb89bfab4e6c4d2|title=Rail spikes hammered, bullet train being built from Sin City to the City of Angels|work=Associated Press News|author=Ritter, Ken|date=April 22, 2024|accessdate=June 9, 2024}}</ref>) is expected to be privately financed.<ref name="NevInd-3BIL">{{cite news |last1=Birenbaum |first1=Gabby |title=Vegas to L.A. high-speed rail line secures $3 billion in federal funding |url=https://thenevadaindependent.com/article/vegas-to-la-high-speed-rail-line-secures-3b-in-federal-funding |work=The Nevada Independent |access-date=5 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231205183606/https://thenevadaindependent.com/article/vegas-to-la-high-speed-rail-line-secures-3b-in-federal-funding |archive-date=5 December 2023 |language=en |date=5 December 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Due to rising costs of labor force and materials, the company requested a $6 billion loan from the U.S. Department of Transportation. The costs are now estimated to be $21.5 billion.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cruz |first=Rene Ray De La |title=Cost spikes for Brightline West's high-speed rail project from Vegas to Southern California |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/news/2025/10/09/brightline-west-southern-california-las-vegas-high-speed-rail-cost/86558671007/ |access-date=2025-10-22 |website=Victorville Daily Press |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Rancho Cucamonga extension===
The company initiated planning on a rail line over the [[Cajon Pass]] to [[Rancho Cucamonga station|Rancho Cucamonga]] in June 2020.<ref name="Burroughs" /> The [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]] passed in November 2021 has billions of dollars for rail projects which provides expanded opportunities for companies such as Brightline.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Varghese |first=Romy |date=2022-04-18 |title=Will a Fast Train to Vegas Lure Road Trippers From Their Cars? |language=en |work=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2022-04-18/high-speed-train-from-california-to-vegas-could-be-a-reality |access-date=2022-05-03}}</ref> In January 2022, the Federal Transportation Department's Federal Rail Administration began reviewing the {{convert|49 |mile|km|adj=mid| segment}} that would allow speeds of up to {{convert|180| mph}}.

The environmental report for the Rancho Cucamonga route was released in October 2022.<ref>{{cite web |title=Comment period begins for environmental report on Brightline West Cajon Pass project |url=https://www.permits.performance.gov/permitting-project/brightline-west-cajon-pass-high-speed-rail-project |website=permits.performance.gov |publisher=Federal Infrastructure Projects Permitting Dashboard |access-date=21 April 2023 |archive-date=March 31, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331014036/https://www.permits.performance.gov/permitting-project/brightline-west-cajon-pass-high-speed-rail-project |url-status=dead }}</ref> The environmental report includes the location of the proposed intermediate station in [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]]. The report notes some mitigation measures will be necessary: temporary impacts on noise and wetlands, temporary and permanent impacts on some threatened or endangered species, visual impacts on views in the San Gabriel and San Bernardino Mountains, and traffic impacts around stations in Hesperia and Rancho Cucamonga. The report concludes that the project "will not result in a significant impact on the environment" or have "disproportionately high and adverse impacts" on low-income or minority populations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Comment period begins for environmental report on Brightline West Cajon Pass project |url=https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/comment-period-begins-for-environmental-report-on-brightline-west-cajon-pass-project/ |work=Trains |date=November 10, 2022 |publisher=Kalmbach Media |access-date=16 April 2023}}</ref> The environmental permit was approved in July 2023.<ref>{{cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=July 14, 2023 |title=High-speed rail receives key approval for link into LA |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/traffic/high-speed-rail-receives-key-approval-for-link-into-la-2872022/ |access-date=15 July 2023 |work=Las Vegas Review Journal}}</ref>

The San Bernardino County Transportation Authority was awarded a $25-million grant in July 2023 from the [[Better Utilizing Investments to Leverage Development|Rebuilding American Infrastructure with Sustainability and Equity]] (RAISE) program to fund design and construction costs of the stations in Hesperia and Apple Valley.{{r|ULA 2023-07-05}}<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/stb-approves-brightline-west-high-speed-rail-modifications-and-extension-across-cajon-pass/ | title=STB approves Brightline West high speed rail modifications and extension across Cajon Pass | date=November 20, 2023 |work=Trains |publisher=Kalmbach Media}}</ref>

===Construction===
[[File:Las Vegas station (Brightline West), parking garage construction 2025-12-23.jpg|thumb|Las Vegas station parking garage construction along I-15 in late 2025]]
Preparatory work involving ground surveys in the right of way of Interstate 15 and recruitment of up to 11,000 workers began in January 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=McLawhorn |first=Jennifer |date=January 18, 2024 |title=Brightline West Will Begin Hiring Workers and Launch Field Investigation Work |url=https://www.rtands.com/passenger/high-speed-rail/brightline-west-will-begin-hiring-workers-and-launch-field-investigation-work/ |work=RT&S |publisher=Simmons-Boardman Publishing Inc}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=De La Cruz |first=Rene Ray |date=January 29, 2024 |title=Brightline West conducts fieldwork in California ahead of high-speed rail groundbreaking |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/news/2024/01/29/brightline-west-conducts-fieldwork-in-california-ahead-of-groundbreaking/72372501007/ |access-date=2024-01-29 |website=Victorville Daily Press |language=en-US}}</ref> A [[groundbreaking|groundbreaking ceremony]] was held on April 22, 2024, at the planned [[Las Vegas station (Brightline West)|Las Vegas station]] site, marking the official start of construction.<ref name="LVRJ 2024-04-19">{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=April 19, 2024 |title=Brightline West to break ground on Las Vegas high-speed rail project |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/local-las-vegas/brightline-west-to-break-ground-on-las-vegas-high-speed-rail-project-3037071/ |access-date=April 19, 2024 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US}}</ref> Heavy construction was scheduled to begin in early 2025,<ref name="LVRJ 2024-09-26">{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=2024-09-26 |title=Brightline West's $3B high-speed rail grant signed; heavy construction to begin in 2025 |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/traffic/brightline-wests-3b-high-speed-rail-grant-signed-heavy-construction-to-begin-in-2025-3177566/ |access-date=2024-09-26 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US}}</ref> with the Nevada DOT saying work could start in April 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schultz |first=Jaclyn |date=2025-02-25 |title=Brightline project 'on budget, on time,' according to new U.S. Transportation Secretary Sean Duffy |url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/2025/02/25/brightline-project-budget-time-according-new-us-transportation-secretary-sean-duffy/ |access-date=2025-03-01 |website=Fox 5 Vegas |language=en}}</ref> However, as of October 2025, the major construction for the rail line is expected to begin in April 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cruz |first=Rene Ray De La |title=Brightline West eyes 2026 for California construction of high-speed rail project |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/news/2025/10/22/brightline-west-2026-construction-southern-california-to-vegas-rail/86812607007/ |access-date=2025-10-22 |website=Victorville Daily Press |language=en-US}}</ref> To oversee this critical phase, former CEO Michael Reininger transitioned to a new role in January 2026 as Managing Director dedicated exclusively to the delivery of the brightline West project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brightline appoints Nicolas Petrovic as new CEO |url=https://railmarket.com/news/business/48762-brightline-appoints-nicolas-petrovic-as-new-ceo |publisher=RailMarket |date=January 2026 |access-date=January 27, 2026}}</ref> 

The company originally aimed to have the line operational for the [[2028 Summer Olympics]] in Los Angeles. However, {{As of|2025|4|lc=y|post=,}} officials now anticipate the line will begin service September 2029, too late for the Olympics.<ref name=":1" /> In January 2026, updated financial disclosure revealed that the estimated cost of the project had risen to $21.5 billion.

Since the groundbreaking, field investigations and early-site activities has advanced throughout both Nevada and California. By mid-2025, Brightline West crews were performing geotechnical borings, utility potholing, and survey operations along the Interstate 15 corridor, including bridge-potholing work near the I-15/SR-210 interchange in Rancho Cucamonga.<ref name="BLWAug2025">{{cite web |title=Brightline West Update: Field Investigation Work in Southern California Advances on I-15 Corridor |url=https://www.brightlinewest.com/media/press-releases/2025/update-brightline-west-field-investigation-work-southern-california-08-18-25
 |publisher=Brightline West |date=August 18, 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref> In California's High Desert, crews expanded operations through Victor Valley and Hesperia, conducting soil sampling and drainage surveys.<ref name="VVDP2025">{{cite news |title=Brightline West field work moves forward along I-15 in High Desert |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/news/2025/07/07/brightline-west-la-to-vegas-rail-field-work-california-interstate-15-hesperia-victorville/84487352007/
 |work=Victor Valley Daily Press |date=July 7, 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref> Field work continued to intensify into early 2026, focusing on the I-15 median preparation

In North Las Vegas, PCM Railone announced construction of a US $20 million concrete-tie production facility dedicated to the Brightline West project, with tie shipments expected to begin in late 2025.<ref name="RTANDS2024">{{cite news |title=PCM Railone AG invests $20 million in Nevada plant to supply Brightline West |url=https://www.rtands.com/news/news-news/pcm-railone-ag-invests-20mm-to-open-facility-near-brightline-west/
 |work=Railway Track & Structures |date=October 10, 2024 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref> According to updated planning documents, main civil works, including embankment grading, drainage, and bridge pier construction, are scheduled to accelerate through 2025-2026, with fully heavy-construction activity beginning by early 2026.<ref name="AsianJournal2025">{{cite news |title=Brightline West high-speed rail on track to connect Southern California and Las Vegas by 2028 |url=https://asianjournal.com/usa/lasvegas/brightline-west-high-speed-rail-on-track-to-connect-southern-california-and-las-vegas-by-2028/
 |work=Asian Journal |date=May 22, 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref>

==Route==
{{Multiple image
| direction = vertical
| width = 250
| image1 = Cave Mountain Interstate 15.jpg
| caption1 = 
| image2 = Interstate15 Ivanpah Valley.jpg
| caption2 = Interstate 15 approaching Cave Mountain, California (above) and in the [[Ivanpah Valley]], [[Nevada]] (below). The line is planned to run in the highway [[median strip]] for most of its length.
}}

The tracks are planned to be laid in the median of [[Interstate 15]], aside from a short section connecting to [[Rancho Cucamonga station|Rancho Cucamonga]] and a section on the east side of the highway approaching the Las Vegas station.<ref>{{Cite news |date=June 30, 2020 |title=Caltrans and XpressWest Complete Lease Agreement |publisher=Caltrans |url=https://dot.ca.gov/caltrans-near-me/district-8/district-8-news/caltrans-and-xpresswest-complete-lease-agreement |access-date=July 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://railroads.dot.gov/sites/fra.dot.gov/files/2023-09/Attachment_A_Project%20Changes_a11y_PDF-A.pdf|title=Project Description|publisher=Federal Railroad Administration|date=September 2023|accessdate=March 29, 2024}}</ref> Sections will pass through federal land controlled by the [[Bureau of Land Management]] and the [[National Park Service]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=June 30, 2020 |title=High-speed rail project gets OK to use I-15 right of way in California |language=en-US |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/local-las-vegas/high-speed-rail-project-gets-ok-to-use-i-15-right-of-way-in-california-2065004/ |access-date=July 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name="sun march 2010" /> While plans at first called for a fully [[double-track railway]] along the route, Brightline intends initially to build the project as a mostly [[Single-track railway|single-track]] route with [[Passing loop|passing sidings]], partly because additional sections were moved to the highway median where space is more limited.<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 September 2020 |title=Digest: Proposed Las Vegas high speed project seeks STB approval of route changes |work=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]] |url=https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/digest-proposed-las-vegas-high-speed-project-seeks-stb-approval-of-route-changes/ |access-date=18 September 2020}}</ref>

In the original plan, the route did not extend into Los Angeles due to the high cost of building rail in urban areas.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schneider |first=Benjamin |date=December 13, 2023 |title=Brightline's new Las Vegas train line could be the start of a U.S. high-speed rail revolution |work=Fast Company |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90997250/american-high-speed-rail-has-never-been-closer-to-reality-can-it-cross-the-finish-line}}</ref> The {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} extension from Victor Valley to the city of [[Palmdale, California|Palmdale]], where it would connect to the [[California High-Speed Rail]] system currently in development, in order to provide service to Los Angeles, was not included in the initial phase.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Expansion and connectivity |url=http://www.desertxpress.com/?page_id=83 |access-date=July 9, 2011 |website=Desert Xpress}}</ref> In June 2012, the new plan included the link between Victor Valley and Palmdale as part of construction for the first phase of the project. Passengers would transfer to [[Metrolink (California)|Metrolink]] to access the Los Angeles area.<ref name="mta" />

In June 2020, the company initiated planning on a rail line south of Apple Valley over the [[Cajon Pass]] to [[Rancho Cucamonga station|Rancho Cucamonga]] to provide more direct Los Angeles service, while not ruling out the Palmdale expansion.<ref name="Burroughs" /> The details of other sections have not been announced. Later phases may include extensions to [[Phoenix, Arizona]]; [[Salt Lake City|Salt Lake City, Utah]]; or [[Denver|Denver, Colorado]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rosenberg |first=Mike |date=July 29, 2012 |title=Bay Area to Sin City? Las Vegas bullet train backers gamble on record loan |work=San Jose Mercury News |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/california-high-speed-rail/ci_21188241/bay-area-sin-city-las-vegas-bullet-train |access-date=November 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=September 16, 2015 |title=China, U.S. Reach Agreement on High-Speed Rail Before Xi Visit |work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-17/china-u-s-reach-agreement-on-high-speed-rail-before-xi-visit}}</ref>

In 2009, XpressWest estimated that it would carry around five million round trip passengers in the first full year of operation,<ref name="fra">{{Cite web |title=DesertXpress&nbsp;– Las Vegas to Victorville Environmental Impact Statement |url=http://www.fra.dot.gov/us/content/1703 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530022611/http://www.fra.dot.gov/us/content/1703 |archive-date=May 30, 2009}}</ref> with the company charging fares of around $50 for a one-way trip between Victorville and Las Vegas.<ref name="sun july 2009">{{Cite news |last=Lisa Mascaro |date=July 2, 2009 |title=Path clears for federal support of fast train to California |work=Las Vegas Sun |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2009/jul/02/path-clears-federal-support-fast-train-calif/ |access-date=October 24, 2010}}</ref> In 2012, the round-trip fare was planned to be around $89 ({{Inflation|US|89|2012|fmt=eq}}),<ref name="rebranding" /> with trains expected to run every 20 minutes on peak, and up to every 12 minutes as demand requires.<ref name="trains">{{Cite web |title=The Trains |url=http://www.xpresswest.com/trains.html |access-date=June 13, 2012 |website=XpressWest |archive-date=July 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706122845/http://www.xpresswest.com/trains.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> {{As of|2020}}, the stated frequency is 45 minutes between departures.<ref>{{Cite news |date=April 15, 2020 |title=Construction on Las Vegas-California train could start this year |work=Las Vegas Sun |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2020/apr/15/construction-on-las-vegas-california-train-could-s/ |access-date=July 17, 2020}}</ref>

In 2023, Brightline West relocated more sections of the route into the median of I-15. The Victor Valley station was reconfigured to have passenger platforms in the highway median. The vehicle maintenance facility was moved from the Victor Valley site to a {{convert|246 |acre|ha|adj=mid|parcel}} west of I-15 in [[Sloan, Nevada]], and will connect to the [[Union Pacific]] mainline at this location.<ref name="VVNG 2023-11-21">{{Cite news |date=2023-11-21 |title=Brightline West's Modified Alignment Approval Brings High-Speed Rail Project Closer to Reality |work= Victor Valley News Group |url=https://www.vvng.com/brightline-wests-modified-alignment-approval-brings-high-speed-rail-project-closer-to-reality/}}</ref>

===Stations===
The [[Las Vegas station (Brightline West)|Las Vegas station]] will be south of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] on [[Las Vegas Boulevard]] in [[Enterprise, Nevada|Enterprise]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Emerson |first=Elaine |date=July 6, 2021 |title=Brightline buys land on Las Vegas Boulevard for planned train terminal |language=en |work=FOX5 Las Vegas |url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/news/local/brightline-buys-land-on-las-vegas-boulevard-for-planned-train-terminal/article_14c070c0-de79-11eb-b688-4f123683ba66.html |access-date=2021-07-06}}</ref> The {{convert|110|acre||adj=mid| site}} is across from the [[Las Vegas Premium Outlets North|Premium Outlets South mall]].{{r|LVRJ 2021-07-06}} The two-story station will feature retail and restaurant space.<ref name="VegasEater2020-02-11">{{Cite news |last=Martin |first=Bradley |date=February 11, 2020 |title=Dine Outdoors at the Virgin Trains Las Vegas Terminal in 2023 |language=en |work=Eater Vegas |url=https://vegas.eater.com/2020/2/11/21132392/virgin-trains-las-vegas-terminal-opening-2023-dining-restaurants |access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> The Las Vegas station on Las Vegas Boulevard was announced in 2020. The land was acquired in July 2021.{{r|LVRJ 2021-07-06}} In April 2023, renderings of the Las Vegas station were released.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=April 22, 2023 |orig-date=April 21, 2023 |title=First look: Brightline's Vegas high-speed train station revealed |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/traffic/first-look-brightlines-vegas-high-speed-train-station-revealed-2765817/ |access-date=April 22, 2023}}</ref>

[[Victor Valley station]] will be in the northeast portion of the town of [[Apple Valley, California|Apple Valley]], adjacent to [[Interstate 15 in California|I-15]] at Dale Evans Parkway.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Brightline West: High Speed Train from Apple Valley to Las Vegas |url=https://www.applevalley.org/services/economic-development/brightline-west |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210523054724/https://www.applevalley.org/services/economic-development/brightline-west |archive-date=May 23, 2021 |access-date=2021-06-04 |website=Town of Apple Valley}}</ref>{{r|VVDP 2021/01/19}}
Passenger platforms will be in the median of I-15 and accessed via walkway under the northbound lanes of the highway.<ref name="ULA 2023-07-05">{{Cite news |last=Sharp |first=Steven |date=2023-07-05 |title=$25M awarded for Brightline West stations in Hesperia and Apple Valley |url=https://la.urbanize.city/post/25m-awarded-brightline-west-stations-hesperia-and-apple-valley |access-date=2023-07-08 |work=Urbanize LA |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=March 4, 2020 |title=Clark County OKs plans for high-speed train station |language=en-US |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tourism/clark-county-oks-plans-for-high-speed-train-station-1971997/ |access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=March 13, 2020 |title=Virgin Trains USA buys land in California |language=en |work=KTNV |url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/virgin-trains-usa-buys-land-in-california |access-date=July 1, 2020}}</ref>

A station in [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]] will be built in the median of I-15 at the Joshua St exit.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akers |first=Mick |date=August 2022 |title=Sisolak believes LV-LA high-speed train will come to fruition |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/news-columns/road-warrior/will-this-be-the-year-the-lv-la-high-speed-train-leaves-the-station-2616212/ |access-date=2023-02-18 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US}}</ref> Trains will make limited stops here in the morning and evening.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 5, 2022 |title=Hesperia Passenger Station Proposed for Cajon Pass High-Speed Rail System connecting Hesperia to Rancho Cucamonga |work=Victor Valley News Group |url=https://www.vvng.com/hesperia-passenger-station-proposed-for-cajon-pass-high-speed-rail-system-connecting-hesperia-to-rancho-cucamonga/}}</ref>

The line will continue into the [[Greater Los Angeles]] area, terminating at [[Rancho Cucamonga station|Rancho Cucamonga Metrolink station]].<ref name="July2020" /> Service to a planned transit center incorporating the station will operate under the jurisdiction of the [[San Bernardino County Transportation Authority]] (SBCTA).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cruz |first=Rene Ray De La |date=October 27, 2021 |title=Brightline adds Rancho Cucamonga to high-speed rail project bound for Las Vegas |language=en-US |work=Victor Valley Daily Press |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/business/transportation/2021/10/27/brightline-adds-rancho-cucamonga-high-speed-rail-project-las-vegas/8574094002/ |access-date=2021-10-28}}</ref> SBCTA and the city of Rancho Cucamonga approved the sale of a {{convert|5|acre|ha|adj=mid|parcel}} to Brightline for the high speed rail station in 2022.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Darling |first=Jordan B. |date=27 October 2022 |title=Rancho Cucamonga, SBCTA approve sale of 5 acres for high-speed rail station |work=The Sun |url=https://www.sbsun.com/2022/10/27/rancho-cucamonga-sbcta-approve-sale-of-5-acres-for-high-speed-rail-station/ |access-date=28 October 2022}}</ref> A proposed {{convert|4.5|km|mi|order=flip}} [[San Bernardino County Transportation Authority#Tunnel to Ontario International Airport Project|underground people-mover]] would provide a link to the [[Ontario International Airport]]. [[Omnitrans]] currently offers direct bus service to the airport from this station.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lin |first=Summer |date=2022-07-27 |title=Elon Musk abandoned plans for a four-mile tunnel at Ontario airport. Locals are picking it up |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-07-27/elon-musk-abandons-plans-for-ontario-airport-tunnel |access-date=2023-01-12 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Rancho Cucamonga, SBCTA move progress sale of Cucamonga Station to Brightline West |url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/press-release/21283041/san-bernardino-county-transportation-authority-sbcta-rancho-cucamonga-sbcta-move-progress-sale-of-cucamonga-station-to-brightline-west |author=Brightline |publisher=Mass Transit Magazine |access-date=11 January 2023}}</ref>

===High Desert Corridor===
[[File:CAHSR connections south.svg|thumb|The High Desert Corridor along with current and planned future rail connections in Southern California.]]
{{Main|High Desert Corridor}}

The High Desert Corridor is a proposed high-speed rail connection between Brightline West and [[California High-Speed Rail]]. It will connect [[Victor Valley station]] and [[Palmdale station]]. At Palmdale, passengers can connect to the existing Metrolink service or continue into [[Los Angeles]] using California High-Speed Rail's tracks.{{r|Forb 2020/08/22}}

===Right-of-way agreements===
In June 2020, the company entered into an agreement to lease the state-owned Interstate 15 right-of-way between Las Vegas and Victor Valley from [[Caltrans]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lilly |first=Caitlin |date=June 30, 2020 |title=XpressWest receives permission to use I-15 right-of-way in California |work=KVVU-TV |url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/news/xpresswest-receives-permission-to-use-i-15-right-of-way-in-california/article_ace4f210-baf1-11ea-a5ca-c77b8a76754d.html |access-date=July 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name="July2020">{{Cite news |last=Sharp |first=Steven |date=July 7, 2020 |title=High-Speed Train to Las Vegas Takes Another Step Forward |language=en |work=Urbanize LA |url=https://urbanize.la/post/high-speed-train-las-vegas-takes-another-step-forward |access-date=July 7, 2020 |archive-date=July 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200707223710/https://urbanize.la/post/high-speed-train-las-vegas-takes-another-step-forward |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=June 30, 2020 |title=High-speed train company receives permission to use I-15 right-of-way in California |language=en |work=KTNV |url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/high-speed-train-company-receives-permission-to-use-i-15-right-of-way-in-california |access-date=July 1, 2020}}</ref> The 50-year lease is in the amount of $842,000 per year starting in 2020, adjusted according to the consumer price index every three years.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Parsons |first=Jim |date=July 8, 2020 |title=Vegas-LA High-Speed Rail Line Can Use Interstate 15 Right-of-Way |work=Engineering News-Record |url=https://www.enr.com/articles/49684-vegas-la-high-speed-rail-line-can-use-interstate-15-right-of-way |access-date=July 17, 2020}}</ref> A similar agreement for the Apple Valley to [[Rancho Cucamonga, California|Rancho Cucamonga]] segment was signed in March 2023.<ref>{{Cite news |last=De La Cruz |first=Rene Ray |date=March 14, 2023 |title=Brightline, Caltrans to sign pact for Apple Valley to Rancho Cucamonga rail line |url=https://www.vvdailypress.com/story/news/2023/03/14/brightline-caltrans-to-ink-pact-for-rail-line-from-apple-valley-south/70001693007/ |access-date=2023-03-15 |work=Victorville Daily Press |language=en-US}}</ref>

Brightline entered into a [[memorandum of understanding]] (MOU) with the [[San Bernardino County Transportation Authority]] in 2020 for the spur between Apple Valley to Rancho Cucamonga, as it provided connectivity within the [[Inland Empire]].<ref name="July2020" /><ref name="Burroughs">{{Cite news |last=Burroughs |first=David |date=July 2, 2020 |title=Virgin Trains plans extension of LA – Las Vegas high-speed line |work=International Railway Journal |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/high-speed/virgin-trains-plans-extension-of-la-las-vegas-high-speed-line/ |access-date=July 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Metrolink (California)|Metrolink]] also approved a MOU to study the links to the Rancho Cucamonga and Palmdale Metrolink stations.<ref name="Forb 2020/08/22">{{Cite magazine |last=Ohnsman |first=Alan |date=August 22, 2020 |title=High-Speed Rail Heats Up In California As Brightline Eyes Las Vegas Route Extensions |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2020/08/22/high-speed-rail-heats-up-in-california-as-brightline-eyes-las-vegas-route-extensions/ |magazine=Forbes |language=en |access-date=2020-09-26}}</ref> A MOU was signed in October 2021 with the [[California State Transportation Agency]] (CalSTA), Caltrans, and California High-Speed Rail Authority, for the use of {{convert|48| miles}} within Interstate 15 to Rancho Cucamonga.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Luczak |first=Marybeth |date=2021-10-22 |title=Brightline West Project Advancing in California |language=en-US |work=Railway Age |url=https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/intercity/brightline-west-project-advancing-in-california/ |access-date=2021-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |date=21 Oct 2021 |title=Brightline West on Track to Rancho Cucamonga |url=https://www.gobrightline.com/press-room/brightline-west-track-rancho-cucamonga |publisher=Brightline |access-date=January 5, 2023 |archive-date=November 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123215936/https://www.gobrightline.com/press-room/brightline-west-track-rancho-cucamonga |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Environmental impact===
The Brightline West project underwent detailed federal and state environmental reviews led by the Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) and Caltrans. The final Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) was approved in July 2023, determining that the rail line would not cause significant adverse impacts with appropriate mitigation measures.<ref name="FRAEIS2023">{{cite web |title=Federal Railroad Administration Issues Final Environmental Impact Statement for Brightline West |url=https://railroads.dot.gov/environment/environmental-reviews/brightline-west-eis-2023
 |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration |date=July 17, 2023 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref>

===Wildlife crossings===
A {{Convert|6|foot||adj=mid|-high concrete barrier}} will keep vehicles away from the rail line along the center divider of Interstate 15. This will prevent animals from making what is already a dangerous crossing of the freeway. [[Desert bighorn sheep]] once thrived in these mountain ranges, though they now face many challenges. Wildlife researchers determined that [[wildlife crossing]]s at [[Soda Mountains|Soda]], [[Cady Mountains|Cady]] and [[Clark Mountain Range|Clark]] mountains could help sustain the sheep and other wildlife.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sahagún |first=Louis |date=2021-09-16 |title=High-speed train to Las Vegas is hailed as an eco jackpot. But will it harm desert sheep? |url=https://www.latimes.com/environment/story/2021-09-16/naturalists-demand-wildlife-bridge-for-las-vegas-rail-line |access-date=2023-03-09 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US}}</ref>

Under an agreement with Caltrans and the [[California Department of Fish and Wildlife]], wildlife crossings will cross over the freeway and the rail line at the three proposed locations.{{r|LVRJ 2023-02-15}} Hundreds of existing [[culvert]]s and crossings under the Interstate will be maintained or improved. Fencing to protect the [[desert tortoise]] and to exclude wildlife will be restored or installed as part of the project.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Martinez |first=Christian |date=2023-02-16 |title=As trains tear from L.A. to Vegas at 180 mph, bighorn sheep will have safe passage |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-02-16/wildlife-crossings-high-speed-l-a-vegas-rail-line |access-date=2023-03-09 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US}}</ref>

Brightline West has also pledged to offset its construction-related emission through pilot programs using battery-electric machinery and [[Solar power|solar-powered]] construction offices.<ref name="BLWSustain2025">{{cite web |title=Brightline West Sustainability Update 2025 |url=https://www.brightlinewest.com/media/reports/2025-sustainability-update
 |publisher=Brightline West |date=March 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref>

==Rolling stock==
{{Multiple image
| direction         = vertical
| width             = 250
| image1            = Wagen Velaro Novo.jpg
| caption1          = Prototype car of [[Siemens Velaro#Velaro Novo|Siemens Velaro Novo]] high speed train, similar to platform proposed for Brightline West
}}

Vehicles will require a high [[power-to-weight ratio]] to climb steep grades on the planned route – up to 4.5% between Victorville and Las Vegas,<ref name="FRAenv">{{Cite report |url=https://railroads.dot.gov/rail-network-development/environment/environmental-reviews/brightline-west-las-vegas-victor-valley-hold |title=DesertXpress "XpressWest" – Las Vegas to Victorville environmental review |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration}}</ref> and up to 6% through Cajon Pass.<ref>{{cite web |date=December 20, 2005 |title=I-15 Comprehensive Corridor Study |url=https://www.gosbcta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/I-Comprehensive-Corridor-Study.pdf |publisher=San Bernardino County Transportation Authority |page=4 |quote=steep grades approaching 6% sustained for approximately 5 miles through the Cajon Pass...}}</ref>

Brightline was in active discussion until mid-2024 with [[Alstom]] and [[Siemens Mobility]] to procure rolling stock for the service and for potential future routes.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mann |first=Ted |date=2023-09-06 |title=European Rail Giants Fight for Slice of U.S. High-Speed Train Line |newspaper=WSJ |url=https://www.wsj.com/business/european-rail-giants-fight-for-slice-of-u-s-high-speed-train-line-e2b788a2}}</ref><ref>
{{Cite web |date=2023-05-23 |title=Brightline West Presentation (High Speed Rail 2023 Conference) |website=youtube.com |publisher=US High Speed Rail Association |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qHclnoItOFA|format=video}}</ref> In May 2024, Siemens announced that Brightline had selected them as the preferred train vendor for Brightline West service.<ref name=":0">{{cite press release |publisher=Siemens Mobility |date=2024-05-01 |title=Brightline West Selects Siemens To Manufacture High Speed Rail Train Sets |url=https://www.mobility.siemens.com/us/en/company/newsroom/press-releases/brightline-west-selects-siemens-to-manufacture-high-speed-rail-train-sets.html |access-date=2024-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240501193234/https://www.mobility.siemens.com/us/en/company/newsroom/press-releases/brightline-west-selects-siemens-to-manufacture-high-speed-rail-train-sets.html |archive-date=2024-05-01 |url-status=live}}</ref> The initial order consists of 10 seven-car American Pioneer 220 trainsets, with a capacity of 434–450 passengers.<ref name=":0" />

The service plans to use the American Pioneer 220, an American variant of the [[Siemens Velaro#Velaro Novo|Siemens Velaro Novo]] high-speed electric multiple unit.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-03-14 |title=FRA-2020-0096 Decision Letter 2023 |url=https://www.regulations.gov/document/FRA-2020-0096-0010 |access-date=2023-03-23 |website=www.regulations.gov |publisher=[[Federal Railroad Administration]]}}</ref><ref name="siemens_americanpioneer">{{cite web|url=https://www.mobility.siemens.com/us/en/portfolio/rail/rolling-stock/high-speed-and-intercity-trains/american-pioneer-220.html|title=The American Pioneer 220: High Speed Rail for the U.S.|website=Siemens Mobility Global}}</ref> Brightline would be the first customer of the Siemens Velaro Novo platform, which has been tested in Germany using the [[ICE S|ICE-S train]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=ICE S auf Messfahrt mit dem EWET – Nürnberger Eisenbahnfreunde e.V. |date=October 30, 2021 |url=https://www.nef-online.de/ice-s-auf-messfahrt-mit-dem-ewet/ |access-date=2023-03-09 |language=de-DE}}</ref>{{r|VVDP 2021/01/19}}<ref name="Forbes2020">{{Cite news |last=Ohnsman |first=Alan |date=25 September 2020 |title=Rail Startup Brightline Kicks Off $3.2 Billion Bond Sale For LA-To-Vegas High-Speed Train |work=[[Forbes]] |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2020/09/25/rail-startup-brightline-kicks-off-32-billion-bond-sale-for-la-to-vegas-high-speed-train/#317359e3ba03 |access-date=26 September 2020}}</ref> and has a designed top speed of {{convert|360|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip|round=5}}.<ref name="velaronovo2">{{cite web |date=2018-06-13 |title=Siemens reveals Velaro Novo 360 km/h train concept |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/siemens-reveals-velaro-novo-360-kmh-train-concept.html |website=[[Railway Gazette International]] |access-date=May 4, 2024 |archive-date=November 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109031753/https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/siemens-reveals-velaro-novo-360-kmh-train-concept.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Velaro Novo |url=https://www.mobility.siemens.com/global/en/portfolio/rail/rolling-stock/high-speed-and-intercity-trains/velaro-novo.html |access-date= |website=Siemens Mobility Global |language=en}}</ref>

The service will use up to 25 train pairs,<ref name="Simmons-2024" /> traveling up to {{convert|200| mph}},<ref name=GoBrightline /> at 45 minute intervals.<ref name="Simmons-2024">{{Cite news |last=Simmons |first=Mark |date=2024-01-22 |title=Brightline West starts preparatory works |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/high-speed/brightline-west-starts-preparatory-works/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240122201858/https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/high-speed/brightline-west-starts-preparatory-works/ |archive-date=2024-01-22 |access-date=2024-01-22 |work=International Railway Journal}}</ref>

The Siemens rolling stock will be assembled at a new factory in [[Horseheads (village), New York|Horseheads, New York]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=September 9, 2024 |title=First US high-speed rail production facility to set up shop in Horseheads, New York |url=https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/first-us-high-speed-rail-production-facility-to-set-up-shop-in-horseheads-new-york/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240911182110/https://www.trains.com/trn/news-reviews/news-wire/first-us-high-speed-rail-production-facility-to-set-up-shop-in-horseheads-new-york/ |archive-date=2024-09-11 |access-date=September 9, 2024 |work=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]]}}</ref>

In 2025, Siemens Mobility began detailed work on the American Pioneer 220 trainsets, incorporating energy-efficient systems and interior layouts customized for the Las Vegas-Southern California corridor.<ref name="SiemensDesign2025">{{cite news |title=Siemens unveils design updates for Brightline West's high-speed trains |url=https://www.trains.com/news/news-wire/siemens-unveils-design-updates-for-brightline-west-high-speed-trains/
 |work=Trains Magazine |date=June 10, 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref> Each train will feature two service classes, onboard [[Wi-Fi]], touchless ticketing, and dedicated accessibility areas. Siemens confirmed that the units will meet full Buy America standards, with the majority of components produced domestically, including traction systems and bogies manufactured in Sacramento, California.<ref name="RailwayAge2025">{{cite news |title=Brightline West trainsets to meet Buy America standards |url=https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/high-speed/brightline-west-trainsets-to-meet-buy-america-standards/
 |work=Railway Age |date=August 20, 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref>

The Horseheads facility, which opened in late 2024, will serve as Siemens Mobility's North American high-speed rail assembly hub, producing Brightline West's carshells, final train integration, and testing before delivery to Nevada for commissioning.<ref name="RailwayGazette2025">{{cite web |title=Siemens Horseheads plant begins work on Brightline West high-speed trainsets |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/rolling-stock/siemens-horseheads-plant-begins-work-on-brightline-west-high-speed-trainsets/66182.article
 |publisher=Railway Gazette International |date=May 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref> Siemens has indicated that the first completed trainset is expected to roll out by late 2027, allowing for testing and certification  ahead of the planned 2029 service launch.<ref name="BLWProduction2025">{{cite web |title=Brightline West Train Production Timeline Update |url=https://www.brightlinewest.com/media/updates/2025-train-production-timeline
 |publisher=Brightline West |date=October 2025 |access-date=November 4, 2025}}</ref>

==Impacts==
[[Oak View Group]] plans a 20,000-seat [[arena]] on a {{Convert|25|acre|adj=on}} site adjacent to the [[Las Vegas station (Brightline West)|Las Vegas station]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Golden |first1=Jessica |last2=Brewer |first2=Contessa |date=March 30, 2022 |title=Stadium developer plans $3 billion sports arena and casino project in Las Vegas |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/03/30/las-vegas-sports-district-3-billion-arena-hotel-and-casino-project-planned.html |access-date=May 3, 2022 |work=[[CNBC]] |language=en}}</ref> This project is part of a larger {{Convert|66|acre|adj=on}} development envisioned as a sports and entertainment district.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stutz |first=Howard |date=June 15, 2023 |title=Vegas basketball arena developer says $10B project is growing, won't require public money |url=https://thenevadaindependent.com/article/vegas-basketball-arena-developer-says-10b-project-is-growing-wont-require-public-money |access-date=January 16, 2024 |work=[[The Nevada Independent]] |language=en}}</ref> According to [[Tim Leiweke]], CEO of Oak View Group, this is a prime location for future growth in Las Vegas' gaming and entertainment corridor.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Oak View Group Acquires 25 Acres in Las Vegas With Vision to Build Retail & Entertainment District Including 20,000 Seat Arena, Casino and Hotel |date=March 30, 2022 |publisher=[[Oak View Group]] |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/oak-view-group-acquires-25-acres-in-las-vegas-with-vision-to-build-retail--entertainment-district-including-20-000-seat-arena-casino-and-hotel-301513837.html |language=en |via=[[PR Newswire]] |access-date=January 16, 2024}}</ref>

{{ill|PCM Railone AG|de|Railone}} announced in June 2024 that they would build a production facility for [[concrete tie]]s and open a North American headquarters in [[North Las Vegas, Nevada|North Las Vegas]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hemmersmeier |first=Sean |date=2024-06-25 |title=German railway manufacturer to open $20M facility in North Las Vegas |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/german-railway-manufacturer-to-open-20m-facility-in-north-las-vegas-3074730/ |access-date=2024-06-27 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US}}</ref>

==Early project development==
===DesertXpress===
The original plan under the name ''DesertXpress'' was to provide an alternative to automobile travel and airline travel between the [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]] area and the Las Vegas area along [[Interstate 15]]. The city of [[Victorville, California|Victorville]] was selected as the location for the westernmost [[Terminal station|terminal]], as extending the train line farther into the [[Los Angeles Basin]] through the [[Cajon Pass]] was considered to be prohibitively expensive.<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 25, 2006 |title=KVBC Las Vegas Story |publisher=[[KSNV-DT|KVBC]] Television. Las Vegas, Nevada |url=http://www.kvbc.com/Global/story.asp?S=5167300 |access-date=October 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201415/http://www.kvbc.com/Global/story.asp?S=5167300 |archive-date=September 27, 2007}}</ref> The station would include free parking and through-checking of baggage straight to the [[Las Vegas Strip]] resorts.<ref name="sun march 2010">{{Cite news|last=Richard N. Velotta |date=March 25, 2010 |title=Work on high-speed rail set to begin this year |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/mar/25/work-high-speed-rail-set-begin-year/ |access-date=October 24, 2010 |work=Las Vegas Sun}}</ref> A future extension would have included a new link to the [[California High-Speed Rail]] station in [[Palmdale]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard N. |date=October 22, 2010 |title=Pressure on DesertXpress in first run at high-speed rail |work=Las Vegas Sun |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/oct/22/pressure-desertxpress-first-run-high-speed-rail/ |access-date=October 24, 2010}}</ref>

DesertXpress Enterprises, LLC was founded in 2005 to develop, construct, own and operate the high-speed rail project. 70% of the company was held by Anthony A. Marnell II of [[Marnell Corrao Associates]] through his ''DX, LLC'' company. [[Gary Tharaldson]] and François Badeau held 20 and 10%, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018 |title=Conduit Exempt Facility Bondfinancing: DesertXpress Enterprises, LLC |url=https://www.ibank.ca.gov/wp-content/Documents/Board%20Meetings/2018/December%202018/7.%20Staff%20Report%20DesertXpress%20.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420195705/https://www.ibank.ca.gov/wp-content/Documents/Board%20Meetings/2018/December%202018/7.%20Staff%20Report%20DesertXpress%20.pdf |archive-date=April 20, 2020 |access-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=California Infrastructure and Economic Development Bank}}</ref> In 2006, the preparation of a first [[Federal Railroad Administration]]-Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) was started.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=July 14, 2006 |title=Federal Railroad Administration, Environmental Impact Statement: DesertXpress High Speed Train Between Apple Valley, CA and Las Vegas, NV |url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-2006-07-14/pdf/E6-11154.pdf |journal=[[Federal Register]] |volume=71 |issue=135 |pages=40176−40177 |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>

The total cost of the link between Apple Valley and Las Vegas was expected to be around US$5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Maldonado |first=Cinthia |date=August 28, 2019 |title=High-speed train back on track, construction set for 2020 |url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/high-speed-train-to-ca-back-on-track-construction-set-for-2020 |access-date=September 6, 2019 |work=KTNV}}</ref> In March 2010, project planners said they could obtain the full funding amount through exclusively private investors,<ref name="sun march 2010" /><ref name="chsr">{{Cite news |last=Richard N. Velotta |date=March 25, 2011 |title=DesertXpress high-speed rail project rolls forward |work=Las Vegas Sun |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/mar/25/desertxpress-high-speed-rail-project-rolls-forward/ |access-date=May 9, 2011}}</ref> but had also applied for a $4.9&nbsp;billion loan through the federal Railroad Rehabilitation & Improvement Financing program.<ref name="chsr" /> As of October 2011, the start of the project was contingent on receiving a $6&nbsp;billion loan from the federal government, the approval or denial of which was expected in mid-2012.<ref name="hopes">{{Cite news |last=Cy Ryan |date=October 10, 2011 |title=DesertXpress hopes for federal loan, aims for 2012 start on work |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/oct/10/desertxpress-hopes-federal-loan-aims-2012-start-wo/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109090252/http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/oct/10/desertxpress-hopes-federal-loan-aims-2012-start-wo/ |archive-date=November 9, 2011 |access-date=October 28, 2011 |work=Las Vegas Sun}}</ref>

A preferred design was identified with the release of the Final Environmental Impact Statement in April 2011, which began a public comment period that ended in May 2011. The federal government approved the design in July 2011.<ref name="fra" /> The planned route was approved by the [[Surface Transportation Board]] in October 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 27, 2011 |title=STB approves DesertXpress route |url=http://www.progressiverailroading.com/high_speed_rail/article/STB-approves-DesertXpress-route--28643 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509215432/http://www.progressiverailroading.com/high_speed_rail/article/STB-approves-DesertXpress-route--28643 |archive-date=May 9, 2012 |access-date=October 28, 2011 |publisher=Progressive Railroading}}</ref> The trains were to be self-propelled, all [[electric multiple unit]] (EMU) trains with maximum speed of {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name="trains" />

The train would travel at speeds of up to {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} averaging {{convert|130|mph|abbr=on}} and making the {{convert|186|mi|abbr=on}} trip from Victorville to Las Vegas in about 1 hour 24 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gloria Hillard |date=April 30, 2012 |title=Towns Debate Impact of Calif.-Las Vegas Bullet Train |publisher=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2012/04/30/151713700/towns-debate-impact-of-l-a-las-vegas-bullet-train |access-date=June 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |year=2008 |title=Proven, Reliable, Safe Technology |url=http://www.desertxpress.com/technology.php |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612145317/http://www.desertxpress.com/technology.php |archive-date=June 12, 2008 |access-date=August 8, 2008 |website=DesertXpress}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Benjamin Spillman |date=June 28, 2009 |title=DesertXpress on right track? |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/desertxpress-on-right-track/}}</ref> In March 2010, executives with the project said they expected construction to begin in 2010.<ref name="sun march 2010" /> In October 2011, construction was planned to begin in the last quarter of 2012, with completion in the last quarter of 2016, subject to funding.<ref name="hopes" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Progress |url=http://www.desertxpress.com/?page_id=37 |access-date=October 16, 2011 |website=DesertXpress}}</ref>

===Transformation to XpressWest===
In June 2012, the developer announced a new plan to build a network of high-speed rail for the region by expanding to Arizona, Utah and Colorado. The initial phase was to include high-speed tracks, Las Vegas to Apple Valley and Apple Valley to Palmdale.

The {{convert|185|mi|adj=on}} link between Las Vegas and Victorville was designed to be double-tracked which is dedicated for the high-speed trains. The costs of this section was estimated at $6.9&nbsp;billion. The developer would put up $1.4&nbsp;billion in private investment and the rest of funding would borrowed under the Railroad Rehabilitation and Improvement Financing program provided by the [[Federal Railroad Administration]].

Future plans include a link between Las Vegas and Phoenix, Arizona, and another from Las Vegas to Salt Lake City, Utah,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tavss |first=Jeff |date=2023-12-08 |title=Plans for high-speed rail between Salt Lake City and Las Vegas not moving forward |url=https://www.fox13now.com/news/local-news/plans-for-high-speed-rail-between-salt-lake-city-and-las-vegas-not-moving-forward |access-date=2023-12-09 |website=FOX 13 News Utah (KSTU) |language=en}}</ref> and Denver, Colorado.<ref name="network">{{Cite web |title=The Network |url=http://www.xpresswest.com/network.html |access-date=June 13, 2012 |website=XpressWest |archive-date=April 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428130640/http://xpresswest.com/network.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> The project was rebranded to ''XpressWest'' to reflect the expanded mission.<ref name="rebranding">{{Cite news |last=Richard N. Velotta |date=June 11, 2012 |title=DesertXpress Vegas-California rail project renamed |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2012/06/11/state/n143538D79.DTL |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612010222/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2012/06/11/state/n143538D79.DTL |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 12, 2012 |access-date=June 13, 2012}}</ref>

DesertXpress Enterprises signed a document with [[Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] officials in June 2012 to explore the plan to build a {{convert|50|mi|adj=on}} high-speed rail link between Victor Valley and Palmdale. The link would initially connect to the [[Metrolink (California)|Metrolink]] system in Palmdale. This would allow passengers to complete a train ride between Los Angeles and Las Vegas with one transfer, by using Metrolink in the Los Angeles area and a transfer to the high-speed train at Palmdale station. The station would eventually connect with [[California High-Speed Rail]], and is designed to have the same specifications and technology, allowing it to continue on California High-Speed Rail further into [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] and [[Los Angeles]]. The early estimate of the costs for this link was $1.5&nbsp;billion. and the earliest environmental work was to be completed by the end of 2013. The date of the service for this link has not been determined.<ref name="mta">{{Cite news |last=Richard N. Velotta |date=June 7, 2012 |title=DesertXpress inks deal to add train link from Victorville to Palmdale, making travel to L.A. possible |work=Vegas Inc. |url=http://www.vegasinc.com/news/2012/jun/07/desertxpress-inks-deal-add-train-link-victorville-/ |url-status=dead |access-date=June 13, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026031323/http://www.vegasinc.com/business/real-estate/2012/jun/07/desertxpress-inks-deal-add-train-link-victorville-/ |archive-date=2014-10-26}}</ref>

===Joint venture===
In February 2013, the federal loan remained unapproved and construction was not expected to start until mid-2014 at the earliest.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 30, 2017 |title=High Speed Rail To Las Vegas Breaks Ground 2017 |url=http://www.canyon-news.com/high-speed-rail-las-vegas-breaks-ground-2017/65561 |access-date=February 20, 2018 |website=Canyon News}}</ref><ref name="starting">{{Cite news |last=Laura Carroll |date=February 12, 2013 |title=High-speed train project at least months away from start |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=http://www.lvrj.com/business/high-speed-train-project-at-least-months-away-from-start-190897161.html |access-date=March 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Velotta |first=Richard N. |date=April 22, 2017 |title=Arrival of Las Vegas Raiders breathes new life into high-speed rail project |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/traffic/arrival-of-las-vegas-raiders-breathes-new-life-into-high-speed-rail-project/ |access-date=April 23, 2017}}</ref>

Representative [[Paul Ryan]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Wisconsin|WI]]), the chairman of the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|House Budget Committee]] and senator [[Jeff Sessions]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Alabama|AL]]), the ranking minority member of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Budget|Senate Committee on the Budget]] were the main opponents to the federal loan application of XpressWest. They argued that the project represented high risk to the taxpayer. They wrote to then-[[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] in March 2013 and recommended the administration to reject the loan application.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Demirjian |first=Karoun |date=March 18, 2013 |title=High-speed rail project beset by political mine fields |work=Las Vegas Sun |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2013/mar/18/high-speed-rail-project-beset-political-mine-field/ |access-date=July 23, 2013}}</ref> The letter indicated that the total cost was estimated to be $6.9&nbsp;billion. The $1.4&nbsp;billion would come from the private sources and the remaining $5.5&nbsp;billion would come from the federal loan. The letter cited a taxpayer risk analysis report as a basis of their recommendation.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Letter from Ryan and Sessions to LaHood |url=http://www.budget.senate.gov/republican/public/index.cfm/files/serve/?File_id=af2e546f-cce2-4653-9793-70ef55a79976 |access-date=July 23, 2013 |publisher=United States Senate Committee on the Budget Republicans}}</ref>

In July 2013, there were reports that loan was indefinitely suspended,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Warren |first=Mackenzie |date=July 12, 2013 |title=Feds suspend $5.5B loan application for XpressWest |work=KSNV MyNews3.com |url=http://www.mynews3.com/mostpopular/story/XpressWest-high-speed-rail-Las-Vegas/ULS5lw1abk2ql1Ujlgioeg.cspx |url-status=dead |access-date=July 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019231339/http://www.mynews3.com/mostpopular/story/XpressWest-high-speed-rail-Las-Vegas/ULS5lw1abk2ql1Ujlgioeg.cspx |archive-date=October 19, 2013}}</ref> which were later confirmed by the federal government, which said that it had been suspended in part due to the failure of the application in regard to the "Buy America" policy, which required applicants to use American-made products.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tetreault |first=Steve |date=July 16, 2013 |title=Feds: XPressWest failed to meet 'Buy America' rules for high-speed train |work=Las Vegas Review Journal |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/traffic-transportation/feds-xpresswest-failed-meet-buy-america-rules-high-speed-train |access-date=July 23, 2013}}</ref> Despite the indefinite suspension of the federal loan application, which was viewed as a denial of the application, the developer indicated that the XpressWest project would proceed without providing the details on financial plan.<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 22, 2013 |title=XpressWest vows to proceed, despite federal loan denial |work=Railway Track & Structures |url=http://www.rtands.com/index.php/passenger/intercity/xpresswest-vows-to-proceed-despite-federal-loan-denial.html |access-date=July 23, 2013}}</ref>

In 2014, U.S. Nevada Senator [[Harry Reid]] mentioned that the federal loan request may resurface, but little had been seen so far of the project's continued viability.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 2, 2014 |title=Las Vegas rail service plans have seen starts, stops |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/las-vegas-rail-service-plans-have-seen-starts-stops |access-date=January 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, the [[Nevada High-Speed Rail Authority]] was proposed to look into the feasibility of high-speed rail into southern Nevada from California, possibly XpressWest.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Young |first=Allen |date=May 26, 2015 |title=Nevada joins the high-speed rail bandwagon with plans for Vegas, SoCal link |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sacramento/news/2015/05/26/nevada-joins-the-high-speed-rail-bandwagon-with.html |access-date=May 28, 2015}}</ref> The bill was introduced in April 2015, and was passed by the legislature in May 2015, by a vote of 40–1.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 20, 2015 |title=Vote on SB457 |url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/BillVote.cfm?VoteID=946&fldReprint=2&fldDocTypeCode=SB&fldBillNumber=457&fldBillname=SB457 |access-date=May 28, 2015 |website=Nevada Legislature |publisher=Nevada Legislative Counsel Bureau |archive-date=July 16, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716032500/https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/BillVote.cfm?VoteID=946&fldReprint=2&fldDocTypeCode=SB&fldBillNumber=457&fldBillname=SB457 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was approved by the Governor in May 2015.<ref>{{Citation |title=Nevada Legislature SB457 |url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/history.cfm?ID=1007 |publisher=Nevada State Legislature |access-date=July 15, 2015 |archive-date=July 16, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716025427/https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/history.cfm?ID=1007 |url-status=dead }} (Became Chapter 260 – see [https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/governor.cfm Bills signed by Governor] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716005802/https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Session/78th2015/Reports/governor.cfm |date=July 16, 2015 }})</ref>

In September 2015, XpressWest and the newly formed China Railway International USA, a consortium of Chinese rail industry companies, announced a joint venture to design, build, and operate the service between Las Vegas and Palmdale, with construction planned to begin in September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 18, 2015 |title=US-Chinese joint venture to develop Las Vegas high speed line |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/us-chinese-joint-venture-to-develop-las-vegas-high-speed-line.html |access-date=September 29, 2015 |website=[[Railway Gazette International]] |archive-date=September 26, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926095521/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/us-chinese-joint-venture-to-develop-las-vegas-high-speed-line.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> A CAHSRA spokesperson said that there have been ongoing discussions concerning allowing the trains to use California High-Speed Rail lines to go further into the Los Angeles area, although no commitments had been made.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Makien |first1=Julie |date=2015-09-18 |title=A high-speed rail from L.A. to Las Vegas? China says it's partnering with U.S. to build |language=en-US |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-vegas-la-chinese-high-speed-rail-20150917-story.html}}</ref>

In June 2016, XpressWest announced that the joint venture had been called off. The biggest reason cited for the termination of the joint venture was a federal regulation requiring the manufacture of the high speed trains inside the United States. XpressWest said that they are "undeterred by this development and remains dedicated to completing its high-speed passenger rail project."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Makinen |first=Julie |date=June 8, 2016 |title=China will not build L.A.-to-Vegas rail line – U.S. company calls the deal off |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-xpresswest-rail-line-20160608-snap-story.html |access-date=June 9, 2016 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>

